  </introduction>

  <exercise xml:id="inv3-8-a">
    <title>Calculate Conditional Proportions</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Calculate the proportion of children who developed a peanut allergy. </p>
      <p><var width="15"/></p>
      <p>Then calculate the proportion of children developing a peanut allergy in each group. </p>
      <p><m>\hat{p}_{PA} = </m><var width="15"/>; <m>\hat{p}_{PC} = </m><var width="15"/></p>
      <p>Does this appear to be a large difference to you?</p>
      <p><var width="60" height="2"/></p>
    </statement>
    <setup>
      <!-- Overall proportion -->
      <var>
        <condition number="0.034" tolerance="0.002">
          <feedback><p>Correct! 13/378 ≈ 0.034.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*13/378.*|.*13\s*/\s*378.*">
          <feedback><p>Right fraction! Now enter the decimal value.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>Calculate 13/378.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>How many total children developed a peanut allergy out of 378?</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
      <!-- p-hat PA (peanut avoidance) -->
      <var>
        <condition number="0.060" tolerance="0.002">
          <feedback><p>Correct! 11/183 ≈ 0.060.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*11/183.*|.*11\s*/\s*183.*">
          <feedback><p>Right fraction! Now enter the decimal value.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>Calculate 11/183.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>How many in the peanut avoidance group developed an allergy out of 183?</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
      <!-- p-hat PC (peanut consumption) -->
      <var>
        <condition number="0.010" tolerance="0.002">
          <feedback><p>Correct! 2/195 ≈ 0.010.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*2/195.*|.*2\s*/\s*195.*">
          <feedback><p>Right fraction! Now enter the decimal value.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>Calculate 2/195.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>How many in the peanut consumption group developed an allergy out of 195?</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
      <!-- Large difference? -->
      <var>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>Response recorded.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>Compare the two conditional proportions.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
    </setup>
    <solution>
      <p>Overall: 13/378 = 0.034 or 3.4%</p>
      <p>Avoidance: 11/183 = 0.060 or 6.0%</p>
      <p>Consumption: 2/195 = 0.010 or 1.0%</p>
      <p>The difference is 5 percentage points, which may not seem large numerically but represents a 6-fold difference.</p>
    </solution>
    <response/>
  </exercise>


  <exercise xml:id="inv3-8-b">
    <title>Fisher's Exact Test</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Use Fisher's Exact Test to investigate whether these data provide convincing evidence that the probability of developing a peanut allergy is larger among children who avoid peanuts for the first 60 months. Do you consider this strong evidence that the peanut consumption effectively deters development of a peanut allergy in this population?</p>
      <hint>
        <p>State the hypotheses in symbols and in words. Define the random variable and outcomes of interest in computing your p-value.</p>
      </hint>
      <aside>
        <title>Two-way Table Applet</title>
        <p>You can use the <url href="https://www.rossmanchance.com/applets/2021/test/ChiSqShuffle.htm?twobytwo=1&amp;hideExtras=1">Two-way Table applet</url> to calculate Fisher's Exact Test.</p>
      </aside>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>H<subscript>0</subscript>: π<subscript>avoid</subscript> = π<subscript>consume</subscript> (no difference in allergy probability)</p>
      <p>H<subscript>a</subscript>: π<subscript>avoid</subscript> > π<subscript>consume</subscript> (higher allergy probability with avoidance)</p>
      <p>Let X = number with peanut allergy in avoidance group. p-value = P(X ≥ 11) where X ~ Hypergeometric(N=378, M=13, n=183)</p>
      <p>p-value ≈ 0.0074, which provides strong evidence that avoiding peanuts increases the probability of developing an allergy.</p>
      <image source="images/Inv3.8solsb.jpg" width="70%"/>
      <image source="images/Inv3.8solsb2.png" width="70%"/>
    </solution>
    <response/>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="inv3-8-c">
    <title>Comparing Proportions</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Would you feel any differently about the magnitude of the difference in proportions if the conditional proportions developing a peanut allergy had been 0.500 and 0.55? Explain.</p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>Yes, a difference of 0.05 (5 percentage points) seems much less impressive when the base rates are 50% and 55% compared to 1% and 6%. The absolute difference is the same, but the relative change is quite different.</p>
    </solution>
    <response/>
  </exercise>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>Discussion</title>
    <p>When the <em>baseline rate</em> (probability) of success is small, an alternative statistic to consider rather than the <em>difference</em> in the conditional proportions (which will also have to be small by the nature of the data) is the <em>ratio</em> of the conditional proportions. First used with medical studies where "success" is often defined to be an unpleasant event (e.g., death), this ratio was termed the <em>relative risk</em>.</p>
  </paragraphs>

  <assemblage>
    <title>Definition: Relative Risk</title>
    <p>The <term>relative risk</term><idx><h>relative risk</h></idx> is the ratio of the conditional proportions, often intentionally set up so that the value is larger than one:</p>
    <p><me>RR = \frac{\hat{p}_1}{\hat{p}_2}</me></p>
    <p>where <m>\hat{p}_1</m> is the larger proportion and <m>\hat{p}_2</m> is the smaller proportion.</p>
  </assemblage>

  <p>The relative risk tells us how many times higher the "risk" or "likelihood" of "success" is in group 1 compared to group 2.</p>

  <exercise xml:id="inv3-8-d">
    <title>Calculate Relative Risk</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Determine and interpret the ratio of the conditional proportions who developed peanut allergy between the peanut avoiders and the peanut consumers in this study.</p>
      <p>Relative risk = <var width="15"/></p>
      <p>Interpretation: <var width="60" height="2"/></p>
    </statement>
    <setup>
      <!-- Relative risk value -->
      <var>
        <condition number="5.85" tolerance="0.1">
          <feedback><p>Correct! 0.060/0.010 ≈ 5.85.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>Divide the proportion with allergy in the avoidance group by the proportion in the consumption group.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>Calculate the ratio of the two conditional proportions.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
      <!-- Interpretation -->
      <var>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>Response recorded.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>Interpret what the relative risk value means in context.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
    </setup>
    <solution>
      <p>Relative risk = 0.060 / 0.010 = 5.85</p>
      <p>Children who avoided peanuts were about 5.85 times more likely to develop a peanut allergy than children who consumed peanuts.</p>
    </solution>
    <response/>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="inv3-8-e">
    <title>Percentage Change</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Because we are now working with a ratio, we can also interpret this statistic in terms of percentage change. Subtract one from the relative risk value and multiply by 100% to determine what percentage higher the proportion who developed a peanut allergy is in the avoidance group compared to the consumption group.</p>
      <p>The proportion with a peanut allergy in the peanut avoidance group is <var width="15"/>% larger than in the peanut consumption group </p>
    </statement>
    <setup>
      <var>
        <condition number="485" tolerance="5">
          <feedback><p>Correct! (5.85 - 1) × 100% = 485%.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>Subtract 1 from the relative risk and multiply by 100%.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>Calculate (RR - 1) × 100%.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
    </setup>
    <solution>
      <p>(5.85 - 1) × 100% = 485%</p>
      <p>The proportion who developed a peanut allergy is 485% higher in the avoidance group.</p>
    </solution>
    <response/>
  </exercise>

  <paragraphs>
    <p>Of course, now we would also like a confidence interval for the corresponding parameter, the ratio of the underlying probabilities of allergy between these two treatments. When we produced confidence intervals for other parameters, we examined the sampling distribution of the corresponding statistic to see how values of that statistic varied under repeated random sampling. So now let's examine the behavior of the relative risk of conditional proportions using the <url href="https://www.rossmanchance.com/applets/2021/chisqshuffle/ChiSqShuffle.htm?twobytwo=1&amp;hideExtras=1">Analyzing Two-Way Tables applet</url> to simulate the random assignment process (as opposed to simulating the random sampling from a binomial process) under the (null) assumption that there's no difference between the two treatments. [Optional: See the <xref ref="tech-detour-two-way" text="custom">Technology Detour</xref> at the end of Ch. 3 for instructions on conduting the simulation with R or JMP.]</p>
  </paragraphs>

