<paragraphs>
    <title>But can we apply a mathematical model to this distribution?</title>
  </paragraphs>

  <exercise xml:id="inv3-8-h">
    <title>Mean Near 1</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Why does it make sense that the mean of the simulated relative risks is close to the value 1?</p>
      <hint>
        <p>Remember the assumption behind your simulation analysis.</p>
      </hint>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>Under the null hypothesis, the two treatments are equally effective, so the ratio of the probabilities should be 1 (no difference).</p>
    </solution>
    <response/>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="inv3-8-i">
    <title>Skewness</title>
    <statement>
      <p>You should notice skewness in the distribution of relative risk values. Explain why it is not surprising for the distribution of this statistic to be skewed to the right (especially with smaller sample sizes).</p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>A ratio can be any positive value. Values close to 1 are restricted to fall between 0 and 2, but large ratios can extend far to the right (e.g., 5, 10, 100, etc.). This creates right skewness.</p>
    </solution>
    <response/>
  </exercise>

  <p><term>Note:</term> If the number of successes in either group equals zero, the applet adds 0.5 to each cell of the table before calculating the relative risk in order to avoid dividing by zero.</p>

<p>In fact, this distribution is usually well modeled by a <em>log normal distribution</em>.</p>
  <exercise xml:id="inv3-8-j">
    <title>Log Transformation</title>
    <statement>
      <p> To verify this, check the <term index="no">ln relative risk</term> box (in the lower left corner, or choose from pull-down menu) to take the natural log of each relative risk value and display a new histogram of these transformed values. Is the distribution of the <em>lnrelrisk</em> well modeled by a normal distribution?</p>
    </statement>
    <choices randomize="no">
      <choice correct="yes">
        <statement><p>Yes</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Correct! After taking the natural log, the distribution should be approximately symmetric and bell-shaped.</p></feedback>
      </choice>
      <choice>
        <statement><p>No</p></statement>
        <feedback><p>Look at the shape of the histogram of ln(relative risk) values. It should be approximately symmetric and bell-shaped.</p></feedback>
      </choice>
    </choices>
    <solution>
      <p>After taking the natural log, the distribution should be approximately symmetric and bell-shaped (normal).</p>
      <image source="images/Inv3.8solsj.png" width="70%"/>
    </solution>
    <response/>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="inv3-8-k">
    <title>Mean of Log Relative Risk</title>
    <statement>
      <p>What is the mean of the simulated <em>lnrelrisk</em> values? Why does this value make sense?</p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>The mean should be close to 0, which makes sense because ln(1) = 0.</p>
    </solution>
    <response/>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="inv3-8-l">
    <title>Standard Deviation</title>
