    </setup>
    <solution>
      <p>ln(5.85) = 1.767. This should fall far in the right tail of the distribution, with a p-value around 0.007-0.008.</p>
    </solution>
    <response/>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="inv3-8-n">
    <title>Change in p-value?</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Has the empirical p-value changed? Explain why this makes sense.</p>
      <hint>
        <p>What does change about the distribution when you take the natural log of every value?</p>
      </hint>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>No, the p-value has not changed. Taking the log is a monotonic transformation, so it doesn't change the ranking of values or which ones are extreme.</p>
      <image source="images/Inv3.8solsn.png" width="70%"/>
    </solution>
    <response/>
  </exercise>

  <paragraphs>
    <p>While the log transformation does not impact the p-value, it does impact the confidence interval. So far you have seen the standard deviation of the null distribution, but that assumes the probability of success is the same for both treatments. Instead, we want to find a standard deviation of the ln rel risk values without making that assumption.</p>
  </paragraphs>

  <assemblage>
    <title>Theoretical Result</title>
    <p>It can be shown that the standard error of the ln relative risk is approximated by:</p>
    <p><me>SE(\ln(RR)) = \sqrt{\left(\frac{1}{A} - \frac{1}{A+B}\right) + \left(\frac{1}{C} - \frac{1}{C+D}\right)}</me></p>
    <p>where <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, <m>C</m>, and <m>D</m> are the observed counts in the 2×2 table of data, with <m>A</m> and <m>C</m> representing the number of "successes" in the two groups. Having this formula allows us to determine the variability from sample to sample without conducting the simulation first.</p>
  </assemblage>

  <exercise xml:id="inv3-8-o">
    <title>Calculate Standard Error</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Calculate the value of this standard error of the ln(rel risk) for this study.</p>
      <p><m>SE(\ln(RR)) = </m><var width="15"/></p>
      <p>Interpret this value.</p>
      <p><var width="60" height="2"/></p>
      <p>How does this compare to the standard deviation from your simulated <em>lnrelrisk</em> values?</p>
      <p><var width="60" height="2"/></p>
    </statement>
    <setup>
      <!-- SE value -->
      <var>
        <condition number="0.762" tolerance="0.01">
          <feedback><p>Correct! SE = √(0.0854 + 0.4949) = √0.5803 ≈ 0.762.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition number="0.76" tolerance="0.02">
          <feedback><p>Correct!</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>Use the formula: <m>\sqrt{(1/11 - 1/183) + (1/2 - 1/195)}</m>.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>Plug the counts A=11, B=172, C=2, D=193 into the SE formula.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
      <!-- Interpretation -->
      <var>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>Response recorded.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>What does this standard error tell you about the variability of ln(relative risk)?</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
      <!-- Comparison to simulation SD -->
      <var>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>Response recorded.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>Is this SE close to or different from the simulation SD? Why might they differ?</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
    </setup>
    <solution>
      <me>SE = \sqrt{\left(\frac{1}{11} - \frac{1}{183}\right) + \left(\frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{195}\right)} </me>
      <me>= \sqrt{0.0854 + 0.4949} = \sqrt{0.5803} = 0.762</me>
      <p>This should be reasonably close to (but somewhat different from) the simulation SD, as we're not assuming the null hypothesis is true.</p>
    </solution>
    <response/>
  </exercise>

  <paragraphs>
    <p><term>Note:</term> The variability in the statistic under the null hypothesis (as estimated by the simulation) should be in the ballpark but not all that close to the variability in the statistic estimated from the data. If we used a pooled <m>\hat{p}</m>, modelling the null hypothesis to be true, the results are usually a bit more similar: Assuming null hypothesis is true: <m>\sqrt{1/6.34 - 1/183 + 1/6.76 - 1/195} \approx 0.543</m>. In a case like this where we have strong evidence against the null hypothesis, using the observed counts is more appropriate than using the SD from the null distribution.</p>
  </paragraphs>

  <exercise xml:id="inv3-8-p">
    <title>Confidence Interval Formula</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Now that you have a statistic (ln rel risk) that has a sampling distribution that is approximately normal and you have a value for the standard deviation of the statistic from <xref ref="inv3-8-o" text="custom">Question 15</xref>, what <em>general formula</em> can we use to determine a confidence interval for the parameter?</p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>statistic ± (critical value) × SE</p>
      <p>For 95% CI: ln(rel risk) ± 1.96 × SE(ln rel risk)</p>
    </solution>
    <response/>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="inv3-8-q">
    <title>Calculate Confidence Interval</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Calculate the midpoint, 95% margin-of-error, and 95% confidence interval endpoints using the observed value of ln(rel risk) as the statistic and using the standard error calculated in <xref ref="inv3-8-o" text="custom">Question 15</xref>.</p>
      <p>Midpoint: <var width="15"/></p>
      <p>95% margin of error: <var width="15"/></p>
      <p>95% CI: (<var width="15"/>, <var width="15"/>)</p>
    </statement>
    <setup>
      <!-- Midpoint -->
      <var>
        <condition number="1.767" tolerance="0.02">
          <feedback><p>Correct! ln(5.85) ≈ 1.767.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>The midpoint is the observed value of ln(relative risk).</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>Calculate ln(5.85).</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
      <!-- Margin of error -->
      <var>
        <condition number="1.494" tolerance="0.02">
          <feedback><p>Correct! 1.96 × 0.762 ≈ 1.494.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition number="1.49" tolerance="0.03">
          <feedback><p>Correct!</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>Multiply 1.96 × SE(ln RR) = 1.96 × 0.762.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>For a 95% CI, the margin of error is 1.96 × SE.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
      <!-- Lower endpoint -->
      <var>
        <condition number="0.273" tolerance="0.03">
          <feedback><p>Correct! 1.767 - 1.494 ≈ 0.273.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>Subtract the margin of error from the midpoint.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>Lower endpoint = midpoint - margin of error.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
      <!-- Upper endpoint -->
      <var>
        <condition number="3.261" tolerance="0.05">
          <feedback><p>Correct! 1.767 + 1.494 ≈ 3.261.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>Add the margin of error to the midpoint.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>Upper endpoint = midpoint + margin of error.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
    </setup>
    <solution>
      <p>Midpoint: ln(5.85) = 1.767</p>
      <p>Margin of error: 1.96 × 0.762 = 1.494</p>
      <p>95% CI: (1.767 - 1.494, 1.767 + 1.494) = (0.273, 3.261)</p>
    </solution>
    <response/>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="inv3-8-r">
    <title>Parameter Estimated</title>
    <statement>
      <p>What parameter does the confidence interval in <xref ref="inv3-8-q" text="custom">Question 17</xref> estimate?</p>
      <p><var width="40"/></p>
    </statement>
    <setup>
      <var>
        <condition string=".*[Ll]n.*[Rr]elative\s*[Rr]isk.*|.*[Ll]n.*[Rr]atio.*|.*[Ll]og.*[Rr]elative\s*[Rr]isk.*|.*[Nn]atural\s*[Ll]og.*[Rr]atio.*|.*[Ll]n.*RR.*">
          <feedback><p>Correct! The parameter is ln(π₁/π₂), the natural log of the relative risk.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>Think about what statistic the interval was built around. We used ln(relative risk), so the parameter is the natural log of the population relative risk.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>What transformation did we apply to the relative risk before building the interval?</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
    </setup>
    <solution>
      <p>ln(π<subscript>avoid</subscript> / π<subscript>consume</subscript>), the natural log of the relative risk</p>
    </solution>
    <response/>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="inv3-8-s">
    <title>Exponentiate Endpoints</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Exponentiate the endpoints of this interval to obtain a confidence interval for the ratio of the probabilities of developing a peanut allergy between these two treatments.</p>
      <p>95% CI for relative risk: (<var width="15"/>, <var width="15"/>)</p>
      <p>Interpret this interval.</p>
      <p><var width="60" height="2"/></p>
    </statement>
    <setup>
      <!-- Lower endpoint -->
      <var>
        <condition number="1.31" tolerance="0.05">
          <feedback><p>Correct! e^0.273 ≈ 1.31.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>Exponentiate the lower endpoint of the ln(RR) interval: e^0.273.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>Calculate e raised to the lower endpoint of your CI for ln(RR).</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
      <!-- Upper endpoint -->
      <var>
        <condition number="26.08" tolerance="0.5">
          <feedback><p>Correct! e^3.261 ≈ 26.08.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>Exponentiate the upper endpoint of the ln(RR) interval: e^3.261.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>Calculate e raised to the upper endpoint of your CI for ln(RR).</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
      <!-- Interpretation -->
      <var>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>Response recorded.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>Interpret what this interval means in context of the peanut allergy study.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
    </setup>
    <solution>
      <p>95% CI for relative risk: <m>(e^{0.273}, e^{3.261}) = (1.31, 26.08)</m></p>
      <p>We are 95% confident that children who avoid peanuts are between 1.31 and 26.08 times more likely to develop a peanut allergy than children who consume peanuts.</p>
    </solution>
    <response/>
