  <exercise xml:id="inv3-8-t">
    <title>Zero in Interval?</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Is zero in this interval?</p>
      <p><var width="15"/></p>
      <p>Do we care?</p>
      <p><var width="15"/></p>
      <p>What value is of interest instead?</p>
      <p><var width="15"/></p>
    </statement>
    <setup>
      <!-- Is zero in the interval? -->
      <var>
        <condition string=".*[Nn][Oo].*">
          <feedback><p>Correct! Zero is not in the interval (1.31, 26.08).</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>Is 0 between 1.31 and 26.08?</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>Check whether 0 falls within the confidence interval.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
      <!-- Do we care? -->
      <var>
        <condition string=".*[Nn][Oo].*">
          <feedback><p>Correct! For a ratio, zero is not the relevant benchmark value.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>Think about what parameter this interval estimates. Is it a difference or a ratio?</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>Consider whether zero is meaningful for a relative risk interval.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
      <!-- What value is of interest? -->
      <var>
        <condition number="1" tolerance="0">
          <feedback><p>Correct! A relative risk of 1 means no difference between the groups.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*[Oo]ne.*">
          <feedback><p>Right idea! Enter the numeric value.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".+">
          <feedback><p>What value of a ratio indicates "no difference" between two groups?</p></feedback>
        </condition>
        <condition string=".*">
          <feedback><p>Think about what relative risk value means the two probabilities are equal.</p></feedback>
        </condition>
      </var>
    </setup>
    <solution>
      <p>No, zero is not in the interval, but that's not relevant. For relative risk, the value of interest is 1 (no difference). Because 1 is not in the interval, we have evidence of a difference.</p>
    </solution>
    <response/>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="inv3-8-u">
    <title>Midpoint of CI</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Is the midpoint of this confidence interval for the population relative risk equal to the observed value of the sample relative risk? Explain why this makes sense.</p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>No, the midpoint is <m>e^{1.767} = 5.85</m>, which equals the observed relative risk. But the interval (1.31, 26.08) is not symmetric around 5.85 because we're working on the log scale and then exponentiating back.</p>
    </solution>
    <response/>
